sub.name: Length
sub.unit: The meter is the length of the path travelled by light in vacuum during a time interval of 1/299 792 458 of a second (17th CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1983)
Based on 1 day = 86 400 seconds, and 1 Julian century = 36 525 days. Refer to The Astronomical Almanac for the Year 1995, U.S. Government Printing Office, Washington, DC, 1994
Approximately, the mean distance between the earth and the sun
The micron was defined as one 1 000 000th of one meter in 1879. Presently replaced with micro meter and excluded from the regal units
A metric unit of length used to specify wavelengths of electromagnetic radiation
A unit of measurement used to specify wavelength of X-ray

A unit of length used in navigation which is equivalent to the distance spanned by one second of arc in latitude. Adopted by the First International Extraordinary Hydrographic Conference, Monaco, 1929
16.5 times US survey foot (= pole or perch)
6 times US survey foot, a unit of measurement for water depth

From 1893 until 1959, the yard was defined as being exactly equal to 3600/3937 m, and thus the foot was defined as being exactly equal to 1200/3937 m, which was called "U.S. survey foot". 1 international foot (0.3048 m) = 0.999 998 U.S. survey foot exactly

sub.name: Mass
sub.unit: The kilogram is the unit of mass, equal to the mass of the international prototype of the kilogram, which is an alloy column made of 90% platinum and 10% iridium, 39 millimeters in diameter and height, preserved in the suburbs of Paris (3rd CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1901)
Used to weigh gems or noble metals. Standardized as 0.2 gram in 1907
A unit to measure mass of elementary particles, atoms and molecules. 1 u is equal to 1/12 of the mass of an atom of the nuclide 12C

sub.name: Electric Current
sub.unit: The ampere is the constant current in two straight conductors, which have infinite length and negligible circular cross section, parallel to each other and placed 1 meter apart in vacuum, and produce a force equal to 2E-07 newton per meter of length (9th CGPM, Conférence Générale des Poids et Mesures, 1948)

sub.name: Radioactivity
sub.unit: Named for Antoine Henri Becquerel, a French Nobel prize winner (1903). Activation of nucleus disintegration. One becauerel is defined as the number of radial rays spontaneously emitted by a radioactive substance in one second, not proportional to radial energy or danger

sub.name: Dose Equivalent
sub.unit: Named for the Swedish physicist Rolf Maximilliam Sievert. Used to measure biological effect by radiation and expresses a degree of danger against human body

sub.name: Absorbed Dose
sub.unit: Named for the English physicist Stephen Gray. An SI unit which expresses energy received by a substance irradiated with ionized radiation
